### Test Bandwidth Usage API Endpoints
### You can use this file with REST Client extension in VS Code or import into Postman

@baseUrl = http://localhost:5000
@tenantId = 65a1234567890abcdef12345
@ownerId = 65a1234567890abcdef12346

### 1. Check Current Bandwidth Usage
GET {{baseUrl}}/bandwidth/check?tenantId={{tenantId}}&ownerId={{ownerId}}
Content-Type: application/json

### 2. Get Bandwidth Statistics
GET {{baseUrl}}/bandwidth/stats?tenantId={{tenantId}}&ownerId={{ownerId}}
Content-Type: application/json

### 3. Track Upload (100MB)
POST {{baseUrl}}/bandwidth/track
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "tenantId": "{{tenantId}}",
  "ownerId": "{{ownerId}}",
  "sizeInBytes": 104857600,
  "operation": "upload"
}

### 4. Track Download (50MB)  
POST {{baseUrl}}/bandwidth/track
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "tenantId": "{{tenantId}}",
  "ownerId": "{{ownerId}}",
  "sizeInBytes": 52428800,
  "operation": "download"
}

### 5. Track Small File Upload (1MB)
POST {{baseUrl}}/bandwidth/track
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "tenantId": "{{tenantId}}",
  "ownerId": "{{ownerId}}",
  "sizeInBytes": 1048576,
  "operation": "upload"
}

### 6. Test Bandwidth Limit Exceeded (10GB)
POST {{baseUrl}}/bandwidth/track
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "tenantId": "{{tenantId}}",
  "ownerId": "{{ownerId}}",
  "sizeInBytes": 10737418240,
  "operation": "upload"
}

### 7. Get Usage Data (includes bandwidth)
GET {{baseUrl}}/usage/{{tenantId}}
Content-Type: application/json

### 8. Test File Upload with Bandwidth Tracking
POST {{baseUrl}}/upload
